    <fr:number>1.1.8</fr:number>
    <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> be a filtered object, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j\colon  X\hookrightarrow  A]]></fr:tex> a sub-object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    The <fr:em>filtration induced by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex></fr:em> (or simply the <fr:em>induced filtration</fr:em>) on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is the unique filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtrations;
    we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^n(X)       = j^{-1}(F^n(A))       = X\cap  F^n(A).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
    <fr:p>Dually, the <fr:em>quotient filtration</fr:em> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/X]]></fr:tex> (the unique filtration such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\colon  A\to  A/X]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtrations) is given by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^n(A/X)       = p(F^n(A))       \cong  (X+F^n(A))/X       \cong  F^n(A)/(X\cap  F^n(A)).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>745</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory II › Filtrations › Filtered objects"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii-1" title="Hodge Theory II › Filtrations"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-ii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-ii" title="Hodge Theory II">Hodge Theory II</fr:link> › Filtrations</fr:link> › Filtered objects</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.1</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>668</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> be an abelian category.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We will be considering <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>-filtrations, finite, in general, on the objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>669</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>decreasing</fr:em> (resp. <fr:em>increasing</fr:em>) <fr:em>filtration</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of an object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> is a family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(F^n(A))_{n\in \mathbb {Z}}]]></fr:tex> (resp. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(F_n(A))_{n\in \mathbb {Z}}]]></fr:tex>) of sub-objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> satisfying
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \forall  n,m       \quad  n\leqslant  m \implies  F^m(A)\subset  F^n(A)     ]]></fr:tex>
    (resp. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\leqslant  m\implies  F_n(A)\subset  F_m(A)]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>filtered object</fr:em> is an object endowed with a filtration.
    When there is no chance of confusion, we often denote by the same letter filtrations on different objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> is a decreasing (resp. increasing) filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then we set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\infty (A)=0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^{-\infty }(A)=A]]></fr:tex> (resp. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{-\infty }(A)=0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_\infty (A)=A]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>The <fr:em>shifted filtrations</fr:em> of a decreasing filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> are defined by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       W[n]^p(A)       = W^{n+p}(A)     ]]></fr:tex>
    for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>670</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a decreasing (resp. increasing) filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_n(A)=F^{-n}(A)]]></fr:tex> (resp the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^n(A)=F_{-n}(A)]]></fr:tex>) form an increasing (resp. decreasing) filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    
    This allows us in principal to consider only decreasing filtrations;
    <fr:em>unless otherwise explicitly mentioned, when we say "filtration" we always mean "decreasing filtration"</fr:em>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>671</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em>finite</fr:em> if there exist <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^n(A)=A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^m(A)=0]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>672</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.5</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>A <fr:em>morphism</fr:em> from a filtered object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> to a filtered object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(B,F)]]></fr:tex> is a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that satisfies <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(F^n(A))\subset  F^n(B)]]></fr:tex> for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Filtered objects (resp. finite filtered objects) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> form an additive category in which inductive limits and finite projective limits exist (and thus kernels, cokernels, images, and coimages of a morphism).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>A morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon (A,F)\to (B,F)]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em>strict</fr:em>, or <fr:em>strictly compatible with the filtrations</fr:em>, if the canonical arrows from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Coim}(f)]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Im}(f)]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism of filtered objects (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.11" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.11.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="1.1.11" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>673</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.6</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(-)^\circ ]]></fr:tex> be the contravariant identity functor from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> to the dual category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}^\circ ]]></fr:tex>.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> is a filtered object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>, then the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A/F^n(A))^\circ ]]></fr:tex> can be identified with sub-objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A^\circ ]]></fr:tex>.
    The <fr:em>dual</fr:em> filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A^\circ ]]></fr:tex> is defined by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^n(A^\circ )       = (A/F^{1-n})^\circ .     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>The double dual of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> can be identified with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex>.
    This construction identifies the dual of the category of filtered objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex> with the category of filtered objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}^\circ ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>674</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.7</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> is a filtered object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>, then its <fr:em>associated graded</fr:em> is the object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}^\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> defined by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Gr}^n(A)       = F^n(A)/F^{n+1}(A).     ]]></fr:tex>
    The convention <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6.xml" number="1.1.6" /> is justified by the simple formula
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Gr}^n(A^\circ )       = \operatorname {Gr}^{-n}(A)^\circ      ]]></fr:tex>
    which follows from the self-dual diagram

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>675</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.7.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.7.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>1.1.7.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.7</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="4c8cf20a648de469d2843c0b0f11c1b9"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
        A/F^n(A)
        && A/ F^{n+1}(A)
          \ar [ll]
        && 0
      \\& A
          \ar [ul] \ar [ur]
        && \operatorname {Gr}^n(A)
          \ar [ul] \ar [ur]
        && (1.1.7.1)
      \\F^{n+1}(A)
          \ar [ur] \ar [rr]
        && F^n(A)
          \ar [ul] \ar [ur]
        && 0
          \ar [ul]
      \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>676</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.8</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(A,F)]]></fr:tex> be a filtered object, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j\colon  X\hookrightarrow  A]]></fr:tex> a sub-object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
    The <fr:em>filtration induced by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex></fr:em> (or simply the <fr:em>induced filtration</fr:em>) on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is the unique filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtrations;
    we have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^n(X)       = j^{-1}(F^n(A))       = X\cap  F^n(A).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>Dually, the <fr:em>quotient filtration</fr:em> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/X]]></fr:tex> (the unique filtration such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\colon  A\to  A/X]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the filtrations) is given by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^n(A/X)       = p(F^n(A))       \cong  (X+F^n(A))/X       \cong  F^n(A)/(X\cap  F^n(A)).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>677</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.9</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> are sub-objects of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X\subset  Y]]></fr:tex>, then on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y/X\xrightarrow {\sim }\operatorname {Ker}(A/X\to  A/Y)]]></fr:tex> the quotient filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> agrees with that induced by that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A/X]]></fr:tex>.
    In the diagram
    
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="a02137ad2b8968d01ad871f220398f31"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
      A/Y
      && A/X
        \ar [ll]
    \\& A
        \ar [ul] \ar [ur]
      && Y/X
        \ar [ul]
    \\X
        \ar [rr] \ar [ur]
      && Y
        \ar [ul] \ar [uu] \ar [ur]
    \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>

    the arrows are strict.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>678</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.10</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.10.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.10</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We call the filtration <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9.xml" taxon="Lemma" number="1.1.9" /> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y/X]]></fr:tex> the <fr:em>filtration induced by that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex></fr:em> (or simply the <fr:em>induced filtration</fr:em>).
    By <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.9.xml" taxon="Lemma" number="1.1.9" />, its definition is self-dual.

    In particular, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma \colon  A\xrightarrow {f}B\xrightarrow {G}C]]></fr:tex> is a **!!<fr:strong><fr:em>TO-DO: o-suite</fr:em></fr:strong>?!!** sequence, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> is filtered, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}(\Sigma )=\operatorname {Ker}(g)/\operatorname {Im}(f)=\operatorname {Ker}(\operatorname {Coker}(f)\to \operatorname {Coim}(g))]]></fr:tex> is endowed with a canonical induced filtration.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>The reader can show that:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>679</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.11</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.11.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.11</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon (A,F)\to (B,F)]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of filtered objects with finite filtrations.
      For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> to be strict, it is necessary and sufficient that the sequence
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         0         \to  \operatorname {Gr}(\operatorname {Ker}(f))         \to  \operatorname {Gr}(A)         \to  \operatorname {Gr}(B)         \to  \operatorname {Gr}(\operatorname {Coker}(f))         \to  0       ]]></fr:tex>
      be exact.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma \colon (A,F)\to (B,F)\to (C,F)]]></fr:tex> be a **!!<fr:strong><fr:em>TO-DO: o-suite</fr:em></fr:strong>?!!** sequence of strict morphisms.
      We then have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}(\operatorname {Gr}(\Sigma ))         \cong  \operatorname {Gr}(\operatorname {H}(\Sigma ))       ]]></fr:tex>
      canonically.
      In particular, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is exact in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}(\Sigma )]]></fr:tex> is exact in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}^\mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In a category of modules, to say that a morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon (A,F)\to (B,F)]]></fr:tex> is strict implies that every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex> of filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geqslant  n]]></fr:tex> (i.e. <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  F^n(B)]]></fr:tex>) that is in the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is already in the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^n(A)]]></fr:tex>:
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[     f(F^n(A))     = f(A)\cap  F^n(B).   ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>683</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.1.12</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.1.12.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>1.1.12</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.1</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\otimes \colon \mathscr {A}_1\times \ldots \times \mathscr {A}_n\to \mathscr {B}]]></fr:tex> is a multiadditive right-exact functor, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_i]]></fr:tex> is an object of finite filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}_i]]></fr:tex> (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1\leqslant  i\leqslant  n]]></fr:tex>), then we define a filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bigotimes _{i=1}^n A_i]]></fr:tex> by
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^k(\bigotimes _{i=1}^n A_i)       = \sum _{\sum  k_i=k} \operatorname {Im}(\bigotimes _{i=1}^n F^{k_i}(A_i)\to \bigotimes _{i=1}^n A_i)     ]]></fr:tex>
    (a sum of sub-objects).</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Dually, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is left-exact, then we set
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^k(H(A_i))       = \bigcap _{\sum  k_i=k} \operatorname {Ker}(H(A_i)\to  H(A_i/F^{k_i}(A_i))).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is exact, then the two definitions are equivalent.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We extend these definitions to contravariant functors in certain variables by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.1.6.xml" number="1.1.6" />.
    In particular, for the left-exact functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Hom}]]></fr:tex>, we set
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^k(\operatorname {Hom}(A,B))       = \{f\colon  A\to  B \mid  f(F^n(A))\subset  F^{n+k}(B)\,\,\forall  n\}.     ]]></fr:tex>
    We thus have
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Hom}((A,F),(B,F))       = F^0(\operatorname {Hom}(A,B)).     ]]></fr:tex>

    Under the above hypotheses, we have obvious morphisms
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \begin {aligned}         \bigotimes _{i=1}^n \operatorname {Gr}(A_i)         &\to  \operatorname {Gr}(\bigotimes _{i=1}^n A_i)       \\\operatorname {Gr} H(A_i)         &\to  H(\operatorname {Gr}(A_i)).       \end {aligned}     ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is exact, then these are isomorphisms and inverse to one another.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>These constructions are compatible with composition of functors, in a sense whose details we leave to the reader.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
